{"cursor":"7108","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"'Toda AznÃ¡rez', also 'Teuda de Larraun' or 'Tota' (c. 885âaft. 970), was the\nqueen-consort of Pamplona through her marriage to Sancho I, who reigned\n905â925, and was regent of Pamplona, 931â934. Later in life, she ruled a\nsubkingdom created for her.\n\nShe was the daughter of Aznar SÃ¡nchez, lord of Larraun, paternal grandson of\nking GarcÃ­a ÃÃ±iguez of Pamplona, while her mother Onneca FortÃºnez was a daughter\nof king FortÃºn GarcÃ©s. Thus, Toda's children were also descendants of the Arista\ndynasty of Navarrese monarchs. She was sister of Sancha AznÃ¡rez, wife of king\nJimeno GarcÃ©s, her husband's brother and successor, while Toda and Sancha were\nalso aunts of Caliph Abd-ar-Rahman III, through their mother's first marriage to\nâAbdullah ibn Muhammad.\n\nWith the death of her brother-in-law Jimeno in 931, she became regent and\nguardian for her young son, GarcÃ­a SÃ¡nchez I. In 934 Toda signed a treaty\npledging allegiance to her nephew Abd-ar-Rahman III, and released hostages of\nthe Banu Di n-Nun clan, the caliph confirming the rule of her son GarcÃ­a (this\nhas sometimes been interpreted as an act of the Caliph to liberate GarcÃ­a from\nhis mother's direct control). This led to the rebellion in Falces by a count\nFortÃºn GarcÃ©s, an \"irascible man who hated Muslims\", the uprising being\nsuppressed with Cordoban arms. Toda violated her treaty in 937, forcing a\npunitive campaign.\n\nDuring several stretches she appears in the royal charters of the kingdom to the\nexclusion of her daughter-in-law, the queen, from 947 to 955, and again in 959.\nIn 958 she was ruling her own subkingdom, in the area of Degio and Lizarra,\ntowns not otherwise identified. Roger Collins, \"Queens-Dowager and Queens-\nRegnant in Tenth-Century LeÃ³n and Navarre\", in John Carmi Parsons, Medieval\nQueenship, 1998, pp. 79-92.\n\nThe same year, she took an interest in the health of her Leonese grandson Sancho\nI, whose obesity was largely responsible for his dethronement. Cantera\nBurgos 1966, [http://books.google.com/books?id=hWAKAQAAIAAJ&q=obesity p.\n363] Hajji 1970, [http://www.google.com/search?tbs=bks%3A1&tbo=1&q=de-\nposed+Sancho+Fat+excessive+corpulence+prevented+riding p. 74] Toda\nrequested the assistance of Abd-ar-Rahman III, the Caliphate of CÃ³rdoba being\nrenowned for its physicians. The caliph sent her his Jewish physician Hasdai ibn\nShaprut, who promised to cure Sancho on condition that Toda visit the city of\nCÃ³rdoba. Nykl 1974,\n[http://books.google.com/books?id=JU4EGnEEeR0C&pg=PA6 pp. 6â7] Therefore,\nToda, her son GarcÃ­a SÃ¡nchez I of Pamplona and grandson Sancho I of LeÃ³n, nobles\nand clergymen arrived in CÃ³rdoba, where they were received with full honors and\namid much pomp. Cantera Burgos 1966,\n[http://books.google.com/books?id=hWAKAQAAIAAJ&q=full+honors p.\n363] VallvÃ© Bermejo 1992,\n[http://books.google.com/books?id=5X1pAAAAMAAJ&q=recibidos+pompa p.\n177] Hajji 1970,\n[http://books.google.com/books?id=zR9pAAAAMAAJ&q=958+nobles p. 75] The\narrival of this Christian queen in the capital of an Islamic caliphate enhanced\nAbd-ar-Rahman III's prestige among his subjects, Guichard 2008,\n[http://books.google.com/books?id=hbZ7ekyXOnwC&pg=PA101 p. 101] and is\nconsidered a landmark in the history of medieval diplomacy. Azizur Rahman\n2001, p. 147 Sancho's medical treatment was successful, and he was\n\"relieved from his excessive corpulence.\" Hajji 1970,\n[http://books.google.com/books?id=zR9pAAAAMAAJ&q=excessive+corpulence p.\n76] Jayyusi 1992,\n[http://books.google.com/books?id=cbfORLWv1HkC&pg=PA37 p. 37]\n\nShe had been an energetic diplomat, arranging political marriages for her\ndaughters among the competing royalty and nobility of Christian Iberia.\n","linknr":182,"url":"Toda_of_Navarre","recorded":1375079216,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Toda_of_Navarre&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Toda_of_Navarre&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.o